        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity and Requested Wavelength Band:

The sensitivity requirement of 7 mJy/beam per 61 kHz spectral resolution element across the 12CO line is designed to provide a peak S/N &gt; 10 across many independent spectral resolution elements.  This same threshold also permits a very sensitive measurement of the dust continuum  with a peak S/N ~ 400 that will be used to provide a high significance measurement of any asymmetry in the continuum.  Our simulations (see Scientific Justification) indicate that these sensitivities are sufficient to measure a planet-induced eccentricity using both the line emission and dust continuum.  Band 6 was selected for its unique access to the 12CO, 13CO, and C18O emission lines, which provide a range of optical depths to probe both kinematic and surface density effects.


Imaging Requirements:
The maximum available baseline lengths (0.18" angular resolution)are necessary to spatially resolve (with several independent beams) the continuum and line emission from our target, which has an expected diameter of ~200 AU for the dust and ~600 AU for the gas.  Since the Cycle 2 extended configurations are missing short spacings (&lt;40 m), a non-negligible fraction of the spectral line emission could be filtered out (thereby diminishing our sensitivity to  any eccentricity at large radii) without devoting some of the requested time to a more compact configuration.  We therefore request a maximum angular scale of 5" to insure that we probe the disk emission over the full range of spatial frequencies.  Our simulations and sensitivity/overhead estimates properly account for this second configuration of the 12m array, as described in detail in Section 7.6 of the ALMA Cycle 2 Technical handbook.


Correlator Setup:

We request data in the dual-polarization mode with 4 basebands.  Two of these (centered at 218 and 233 GHz) are configured in TDM mode to maximize the continuum bandwidth (and thereby sensitivity).  The upper sideband contains one FDM baseband with 61 kHz channels to probe the 12CO(2-1) line at 230.538 GHz (~0.16 km/s velocity resolution; the window is slightly shifted off center of the line, to avoid the noisy edge of the sideband).  The remaining baseband is divided into two narrow spectral windows, each with 61 kHz channels (and half the total bandwidth of the 12CO baseband) centered on the 13CO(2-1) and C18O(2-1) lines at 220.399 and 219.560 GHz, respectively.  We expect an emission line width of 4 km/s, so the specified setup should easily resolve the lines.


Calibration: No special calibration is required.

Bandpass accuracy: Standard calibration is sufficient.

Scheduling/time constraints: None.

Data rate: Within normal limits.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
