    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Gas-rich circumstellar disks host the youngest exoplanetary systems, where the embedded planets are still accreting mass and migrating through the disk.  These planets gravitationally interact with the surrounding gas in the disk; theory predicts that a massive planet can induce disk eccentricities peaking at e = 0.1 - 0.3 and persisting out several times the orbital radius of the planet.  We propose to search for evidence of this planet-disk interaction by measuring the eccentricity of the LkCa15 disk, which is known to host a sub-stellar mass companion, using both the dust continuum and gas line emission.  This program provides: 1) a test for the dynamics of planet-disk interactions, and 2) independent constraints on the planet mass and disk properties.
</prp:abstract>
